Load Data

texts = posts$message
texts <- iconv(texts, 'UTF-8', 'ASCII') # encoding for emojis

Create a Corpus

  • We need to create a collection of documents (Corpus) in the R environment
  • The tm package provides the Corpus() function to do this: 
corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(texts))

Type in corpus to see some information about the newly created corpus:

corpus

<<SimpleCorpus>>
Metadata:  corpus specific: 1, document level (indexed): 0
Content:  documents: 581

Inspecting Content

The summary() function gives more details, including a complete listing of files, but it isn't particularly enlightening..

Preprocessing your Data

  • Data cleansing is tedious, but it is perhaps the most important step in text analysis
  • The tm package offers a number of transformations for cleaning data
  • To see the available transformations:
getTransformations()

[1] "removeNumbers"     "removePunctuation" "removeWords"      
[4] "stemDocument"      "stripWhitespace"

Preprocessing

  • We can also create a custom transformation
  • The tm package provides the ability to do this via the content_transformer function
  • This function takes as input a function which specifies what transformation needs to be done
  • In the following case, the input function would be one that replaces all instances of a character by spaces:
toSpace <- content_transformer(function(x, pattern) {return (gsub(pattern, " ", x))})

Now we can use this content transformer to eliminate colons and hypens:

corpus <- tm_map(corpus, toSpace, "-")
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, toSpace, ":")

Preprocessing

# Convert the text to lower case
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
writeLines(as.character(corpus[[560]]))

come on, group hug! inside out is an academy award nominee for both best animated feature film and original screenplay, and sanjay's super team is up for best animated short.

# Remove numbers
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeNumbers)
writeLines(as.character(corpus[[560]]))

come on, group hug! inside out is an academy award nominee for both best animated feature film and original screenplay, and sanjay's super team is up for best animated short.

Preprocessing

# Remove English common stopwords
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
writeLines(as.character(corpus[[560]]))

come , group hug! inside    academy award nominee   best animated feature film  original screenplay,  sanjay's super team    best animated short.

# Remove punctuations
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removePunctuation)
writeLines(as.character(corpus[[560]]))

come  group hug inside    academy award nominee   best animated feature film  original screenplay  sanjays super team    best animated short

# Eliminate extra white spaces
corpus <- tm_map(corpus, stripWhitespace)

Stemming

  • Typically a large corpus will contain many words that have a common root - for example: offer, offered and offering
  • Stemming is the process of reducing inflected (or sometimes derived) words to their word stem, base or root form
  • For example, changing “car”, “cars”, “car's”, “cars” to “car”
  • Simple stemming algorithms (such as the one in tm) are relatively crude: they work by chopping off the ends of words

The Document Term Matrix

  • Now we need to create the document term matrix (DTM), a matrix that lists all occurrences of words in the corpus, by document
  • In the DTM, documents are represented by rows and terms by columns
  • If a word occurs in a particular document, then the matrix entry for the corresponding row and column is 1, else 0
  • Multiple occurrences within a document are recorded (e.g., if a word occurs twice in a document, it is recorded as “2”“ in the relevant matrix entry)

The Document Term Matrix: example

Doc1 = bananas are yellow
Doc2 = bananas are good

The DTM for this corpus would look like:

Notice that:

  • DTMs can be huge! The dimension of the matrix would be (number of documents)x(number of words in the corpus)
  • The large majority of words will appear only in a few documents; as a result, a DTM is invariably sparse (i.e., a large number of its entries are 0)

Creating a Document Term Matrix

Creating a DTM in R is as simple as:

dtm = DocumentTermMatrix(corpus)

This creates a term document matrix from the corpus and stores the result in dtm.
To get summary information on the matrix just type:

dtm

<<DocumentTermMatrix (documents: 581, terms: 1351)>>
Non-/sparse entries: 2962/781969
Sparsity           : 100%
Maximal term length: 25
Weighting          : term frequency (tf)

Word Frequency

To get the frequency of occurrence of each word in the corpus, we simply sum over all rows to give column sums:

freq <- colSums(as.matrix(dtm))
freq[46:49]

    stuff adventure   cookies    hungry 
        3        12         1         1
  • First, we have converted the DTM into a mathematical matrix using the as.matrix() function
  • Then, we have summed over all rows to give us the totals for each column (term)
  • The result is stored in the (column matrix) variable freq

Word Frequency

Check that the dimension of freq equals the number of terms:

length(freq) == dim(dtm)[2]

[1] TRUE

And indeed:

length(freq)

[1] 1351

dim(dtm)[2]

[1] 1351

Word Frequency

# Create sort order (descending)
ord <- order(freq, decreasing = TRUE)

Then list the most and least frequently occurring terms:

# Inspect most frequently occurring terms
freq[head(ord)]

     76      75      35      34      34      27 

# Inspect least frequently occurring terms
freq[tail(ord)]

   peek     pow  whoosh  beauty   chill sequins 
      1       1       1       1       1       1

findFreqTerms(dtm, lowfreq = 10)

Let's plot!

First, we may create a data frame like this:

wf = data.frame(word = names(freq), # names() allows to get or set the names of an object
                freq = freq)
head(wf)

                   word freq
resolutions resolutions    1
ring               ring    2
friends         friends   17
new                 new   34
year               year    3
sea                 sea    9

Let's plot!

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(subset(wf, freq>10), aes(x = reorder(word, -freq), y = freq)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  labs(x = "", y = "frequency") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))

Wordcloud

library(wordcloud)
wordcloud(wf$word, wf$freq, 
          min.freq = 10, 
          rot.per = 0.15, 
          colors = brewer.pal(8, "Dark2")
)

Wordcloud

library(wordcloud)
wordcloud(wf$word, wf$freq, 
          scale=c(5,0.5), min.freq = 5, 
          random.order = F, 
          rot.per = 0.15, 
          colors = brewer.pal(8, "Spectral")
)

Sentiment Analysis

library('syuzhet')
  • Package syuzhet uses NRC Emotion lexicon
  • The NRC emotion lexicon is a list of words and their associations with eight emotions (anger, fear, anticipation, trust, surprise, sadness, joy, and disgust) and two sentiments (negative and positive)

Sentiment Analysis

sentiment = get_nrc_sentiment(texts)
td = data.frame(t(sentiment))

Sentiment Analysis

td_em  = tdw[1:8, ] # emotions
td_pol = tdw[9:10, ] # polarity

Plot Emotions

ggplot(td_em, aes(x = sentiment, y = count, fill = sentiment)) +
